{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01UjFXSwg3pzbjwS4YUyJtGZ","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"IG-110 graphite specific heat capacity temperature dependence J/kg K HTGR density 1.77\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Here is Everything About Specific Heat of Graphite - East Carbon\",\"url\":\"https://www.eastcarb.com/specific-heat-of-graphite/\"},{\"title\":\"GraphiteMatrixThermal | BISON - MOOSE\",\"url\":\"https://mooseframework.inl.gov/bison/source/materials/GraphiteMatrixThermal.html\"},{\"title\":\"INL/EXT-16-38241 Revision 0 Thermal Properties of G-348 Graphite\",\"url\":\"https://www.osti.gov/servlets/purl/1330693\"},{\"title\":\"Examining the thermal properties of unirradiated nuclear grade graphite between 750 and 2500 K - ScienceDirect\",\"url\":\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0022311519315375\"},{\"title\":\"Rapport BIPM-2006/01 Measurement of the Specific Heat Capacity of Graphite\",\"url\":\"https://www.bipm.org/documents/20126/28125415/bipm%20publication-ID-1661/ecac54bb-1086-ac6c-46a3-6f986951a033\"},{\"title\":\"Phonon Engineering of the Specific Heat of Twisted Bilayer Graphene: The   Role of the Out-of-Plane Phonon Modes\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1503.08335\"},{\"title\":\"Determination of the specific heat capacity of a graphite sample using absolute and differential methods | Request PDF\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/231032839_Determination_of_the_specific_heat_capacity_of_a_graphite_sample_using_absolute_and_differential_methods\"},{\"title\":\"TLR/RES/DE/REB-2021-08 Appendices to the Assessment of Graphite Properties and\",\"url\":\"https://www.nrc.gov/docs/ML2121/ML21215A346.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"ORNL/TM-2011/378 A Review of Stored Energy Release of Irradiated Graphite\",\"url\":\"https://info.ornl.gov/sites/publications/files/Pub32588.pdf\"}]\n\nI found some relevant information about IG-110 graphite. The search results confirm that IG 110 is a nuclear graphite grade whose thermal conductivity has been measured as a function of temperature between 300–1800 K, and there are example ASME Material Data Sheets for IG-110 Graphite.\n\nThe results also indicate that graphite's specific heat is strongly dependent on temperature, with specific heat of graphite plateauing around 0.71–0.72 J/g·K at room temperature (approximately 300 K), and specific heat increasing at high temperatures above ~1000 K owing to thermal excitation of electrons and non-harmonic effects in vibrations.\n\nHowever, the search results don't contain specific data for IG-110's density of 1.77 g/cm³ or detailed specific heat capacity values in J/kg·K with temperature dependence coefficients. For more detailed technical specifications of IG-110 graphite properties, you may want to consult nuclear reactor design databases, vendor technical data sheets, or peer-reviewed studies on HTGR materials.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_014nSoKQZw2ozs6fpCh9kUjQ","session_id":"bf29c1b0-7e93-43a9-86fb-8820c5d1c99e","uuid":"d0f6677c-92eb-4e51-b950-daa76f51e833","timestamp":"2026-07-02T22:14:28.539Z","subagent_type":"general-purpose","task_description":"Collect HTTR design data"}
