{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VjHmsr9cpmdC8Bk6h6pJ4R","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"HTTR beta effective 0.0065 delayed neutron fraction neutron lifetime safety analysis reactivity insertion design\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"How Does the Delayed Neutron Fraction Influence Reactor Kinetics? • Physics Forums\",\"url\":\"https://www.physicsforums.com/threads/how-does-the-delayed-neutron-fraction-influence-reactor-kinetics.929397/\"},{\"title\":\"Delayed Neutron - an overview | ScienceDirect Topics\",\"url\":\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/delayed-neutron\"},{\"title\":\"Delayed Neutrons | Definition & Characteristics | nuclear-power.com\",\"url\":\"https://www.nuclear-power.com/nuclear-power/fission/delayed-neutrons/\"},{\"title\":\"Prompt Neutron Lifetime - an overview | ScienceDirect Topics\",\"url\":\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/prompt-neutron-lifetime\"},{\"title\":\"Delayed Neutron Precursor - an overview | ScienceDirect Topics\",\"url\":\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/delayed-neutron-precursor\"},{\"title\":\"Effective delayed neutron fraction and prompt neutron lifetime of Tehran research reactor - ScienceDirect\",\"url\":\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0306454903000811\"},{\"title\":\"NE-\\\\CRP-~A- 764 Topic-l.1 Evaluation of Delayed Neutron Data for Thermal\",\"url\":\"https://www.oecd-nea.org/upload/docs/application/pdf/2020-07/neacrp-a-1986-0764.pdf\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I found relevant information about the delayed neutron fraction of 0.0065 and related neutron kinetics parameters:\n\nThe effective delayed neutron fraction (βeff) for uranium-235 fuel is approximately 0.0065. This value is significant for reactor safety analysis.\n\nDelayed neutrons have a profound effect on the kinetics of reactor behavior and indeed without delayed neutrons the control of nuclear reactors would not be possible. This is crucial for understanding why the delayed neutron fraction is important to safety analysis.\n\nRegarding neutron lifetime parameters: Although the fraction of delayed neutrons is small (99.32% prompt, 0.68% delayed for U-235), their lifetime of several seconds is very long compared to the 10⁻³ s or less that is the typical lifetime of prompt neutrons.\n\nFor reactivity insertion design, the reactivity due to prompt neutrons alone must be kept to negative values by insertion of absorbers, with total reactivity in operation limited to less than ΔK = 0.0065.\n\nWhile the search results discuss general delayed neutron kinetics principles, they do not contain specific information about the HTTR (High Temperature engineering Test Reactor) or its particular design specifications related to reactivity insertion and safety analysis. To find more specific HTTR technical details, you may need to search specifically for HTTR technical documentation or safety analysis reports.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_014nSoKQZw2ozs6fpCh9kUjQ","session_id":"bf29c1b0-7e93-43a9-86fb-8820c5d1c99e","uuid":"057fc349-91c4-4c5c-8ddb-e530e0dd175e","timestamp":"2026-07-02T22:14:32.448Z","subagent_type":"general-purpose","task_description":"Collect HTTR design data"}
