{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019oNz2SaaAugeypJzNJYavh","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"HTTR vessel cooling system design heat removal \"0.6 MW\" OR \"0.3 MW\" rated water cooling panel natural convection radiation JAERI\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Osti\",\"url\":\"https://www.osti.gov/pages/servlets/purl/1429362\"},{\"title\":\"J-STAGE Advance Publication date : 25 February, 2020 Paper No.19-00536\",\"url\":\"https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/f085/e8da22a32adbb12f2aead6ae807534a76e4d.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"Passive heat removal by vessel cooling system of HTTR during no forced cooling accidents - ScienceDirect\",\"url\":\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/002954939601268X\"},{\"title\":\"(PDF) REACTOR CAVITY COOLING SYSTEM WITH PASSIVE SAFETY FEATURES ON RDE: THERMAL ANALYSIS DURING ACCIDENT\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/publication/335036547_REACTOR_CAVITY_COOLING_SYSTEM_WITH_PASSIVE_SAFETY_FEATURES_ON_RDE_THERMAL_ANALYSIS_DURING_ACCIDENT\"},{\"title\":\"Numerical study of the flow and heat transfer characteristics in a scale model of the vessel cooling system for the HTTR -Nuclear Engineering and Technology\",\"url\":\"https://koreascience.kr/article/JAKO202415754333397.do\"},{\"title\":\"A Small‐Sized HTGR System Design for Multiple Heat Applications for Developing Countries - Ohashi - 2013 - International Journal of Nuclear Energy - Wiley Online Library\",\"url\":\"https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1155/2013/918567\"},{\"title\":\"JAERI-Research 2000-062 JP0150250 STUDY ON NATURAL CONVECTION HEAT TRANSFER\",\"url\":\"https://www.osti.gov/etdeweb/servlets/purl/20175455\"},{\"title\":\"Design and fabrication of the reactor Vessel Cooling System (VCS) in HTTR\",\"url\":\"https://inis.iaea.org/records/h75a9-kty70\"},{\"title\":\"Improvement of heat-removal capability using heat conduction on a novel reactor cavity cooling system (RCCS) design with passive safety features through radiation and natural convection - ScienceDirect\",\"url\":\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0306454918304687\"}]\n\nBased on the web search results, I found relevant information about the HTTR vessel cooling system design:\n\nThe HTTR currently uses a forced convection water-cooled RCCS, with the heat loss through the RPV at the rated operation designed at 600 kW, which corresponds to the 0.6 MW mentioned in your query.\n\nThe vessel cooling system (VCS) is composed of thermal reflector plates, water cooling tubes, fins connected between adjacent water cooling tubes and two water cooling trains, and surrounds the reactor pressure vessel, which removes decay heat from the reactor core by heat transfer of thermal radiation, conduction and natural convection in case of loss of forced cooling.\n\nEach VCS consists of a water cooling loop and cooling panels around the reactor pressure vessel (RPV), and the cooling panels, kept below 90 °C, cool the RPV by radiation and natural convection and remove the decay heat from the reactor core during accidents.\n\nThe VCS consists of a Cooling Water Panel (CWP) and a water circulation system supplying a coolant, with the CWP installed on the surface of the concrete wall of the Reactor Pressure Vessel (RPV) room to remove heat from the RPV by thermal radiation.\n\nThe search results confirm that the HTTR vessel cooling system design incorporates the key elements you mentioned: rated heat removal capacity (0.6 MW), water cooling panels, and heat removal via natural convection and radiation.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_014nSoKQZw2ozs6fpCh9kUjQ","session_id":"bf29c1b0-7e93-43a9-86fb-8820c5d1c99e","uuid":"bff984a3-f388-4cdd-baf7-e2a81a16dee9","timestamp":"2026-07-02T22:14:57.738Z","subagent_type":"general-purpose","task_description":"Collect HTTR design data"}
