{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01JBJJFZpktqmUH9ht3HAfqb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have collected comprehensive design data and logged sources. Here is the full report.\n\n---\n\n# HTTR Public Design Data (steady-state specs, with citations)\n\nAll data below is from steady-state DESIGN / fuel-fabrication / benchmark-design publications. **No LOFC / loss-of-forced-cooling test-result source was opened.** Several LOFC-titled papers surfaced in searches and were deliberately skipped (logged as an incident in `output/sources.md`).\n\nTwo sources carry most of the load and are the ones to cite in the calc note:\n- **INL benchmark modeling report** (design compilation of the HTTR): https://inldigitallibrary.inl.gov/sites/sti/sti/4633194.pdf\n- **IAEA coated-particle fuel-fabrication paper** (Kato, Sawa et al., XA0100873): https://www.osti.gov/etdeweb/servlets/purl/20158164\n- **JAEA official HTTR outline**: https://www.jaea.go.jp/04/o-arai/nhc/en/faq/httr.html\n\n## CORE GEOMETRY / PLANT\n\n| Quantity | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| Thermal power | 30 MW(t) | JAEA outline; INL report |\n| Coolant inlet temperature | 395 °C | JAEA outline |\n| Coolant outlet temperature | 850 °C (rated) / 950 °C (high-temp test) | JAEA outline |\n| Primary He pressure | 4 MPa | JAEA outline; INL report |\n| He mass flow rate | **12.4 kg/s** (rated, 850 °C) / **10.2 kg/s** (high-temp, 950 °C); main cooling removes ~97% of power | Takizuka, HTTR project review, https://www.ne.titech.ac.jp/archive/coe21/eng/events/ines1/pdf/87_takizuka.pdf |\n| Average power density | 2.5 MW/m³ | JAEA outline; INL report |\n| Effective (active) core diameter | 2.3 m | JAEA; INL |\n| Active core height | 2.9 m | JAEA; INL |\n| Diameter incl. removable reflectors | 3.258 m | INL report |\n| Overall (incl. permanent reflector) | 4.25 m dia × 5.25 m high (primary components); permanent-reflector stack ~8 m tall | INL report |\n| Number of fuel columns | 30 | INL report |\n| Fuel blocks stacked per column | 5 (plus 2 top + 2 bottom replaceable reflector blocks = 9 layers) | INL report |\n| Total fuel blocks | 150 | INL report |\n| Control-rod pairs / columns | 16 CR pairs (32 rods): 7 in fuel region, 9 in reflector; inserted in CR-guide columns (3 holes each: 2 CR + 1 RSS) | INL report |\n| Triangular column pitch | 36.2 cm (cold) | INL report |\n\n## HEX FUEL BLOCK & FUEL ROD\n\n| Quantity | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| Block shape | hexagonal prism, pin-in-block | INL; fab paper |\n| Width across flats | 360 mm | INL; fab paper |\n| Block height | 580 mm | INL; fab paper |\n| Fuel channels (holes) per block | 33 (Fuel Zones 1–2) or 31 (Fuel Zones 3–4) | INL report |\n| Fuel channel (hole) diameter | 41 mm | INL report |\n| Fuel rod OD (graphite sleeve) | 34 mm | INL; fab paper |\n| Sleeve thickness | 3.75 mm | INL report |\n| Fuel rod length | 577 mm (sleeve 580 mm) | INL report |\n| Coolant annulus gap (hole − rod) | 3.5 mm (downward flow) | INL report |\n| Compacts per rod | 14 | INL; fab paper |\n| Gap, compact↔sleeve | 0.25 mm | INL report |\n\nNote: an explicit fuel-rod-to-rod lattice pitch was not stated in the opened design docs (only the 41 mm channel diameter and block geometry). If needed, derive it from the block hole pattern in the INL report figures.\n\n## FUEL COMPACT & TRISO\n\n**Fuel compact** (annular/hollow cylinder): OD **26 mm**, ID **10 mm**, height **39 mm**; graphite matrix + dispersed TRISO; ~**13,000** coated particles per compact; TRISO **packing fraction ≈ 30 vol%**. Matrix graphite (natural + electro-graphite + binder) density **1.7 g/cm³**, boron-equivalent impurity **<1.2 ppm**. [INL report; fab paper]\n\n**TRISO coated particle** (A-type driver fuel), from the fabrication paper Table 1 (as-fabricated) and INL Table 3/4 (design nominal):\n\n| Layer | Thickness | Density |\n|---|---|---|\n| UO₂ kernel | **600 µm** dia | 10.63 g/cm³ (97% TD, as-fab) / 10.41 g/cm³ (95% TD, design) |\n| 1st: low-density (buffer) PyC | 60 µm | 1.10 g/cm³ |\n| 2nd: high-density IPyC | 30 µm | 1.85 g/cm³ |\n| 3rd: SiC | 25 µm | 3.20 g/cm³ |\n| 4th: high-density OPyC | 45 µm | 1.85 g/cm³ |\n| Whole particle | **920 µm** dia | ~4.45 g/cm³ |\n\nBoron-equivalent impurity in CFP <3 ppm. [Fab paper https://www.osti.gov/etdeweb/servlets/purl/20158164 Table 1; INL report Tables 3–4]\n\n## ENRICHMENT ZONING\n\n- **12 discrete U-235 enrichments**, range **3.4 – 9.9 wt%** (design intent stated as \"3–10 wt%\"); **core-average ≈ 6 wt%** (also quoted 5.9 wt%). [INL; JAEA; fab paper]\n- Arrangement: **4 radial fuel zones × 5 axial layers**. All compacts within one assembly share one enrichment. Enrichment increases from core center outward (radial peaking flattening) and decreases from top layer toward bottom (axial); layers 4 and 5 use the same enrichment. [INL report §3.2, Table 2]\n- INL Table 2 (enrichment wt% by zone/layer):\n\n| Layer | Zone 1 | Zone 2 | Zone 3 | Zone 4 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | 6.7 | 7.9 | 9.4 | 9.9 |\n| 2 | 5.2 | 6.3 | 7.2 | 7.9 |\n| 3 | 4.3 | 5.2 | 5.9 | 6.3 |\n| 4 | 3.4 | 3.9 | 4.3 | 4.8 |\n| 5 | 3.4 | 3.9 | 4.3 | 4.8 |\n\n## BURNABLE POISON\n\n- Composition: **B₄C + C (graphite) sintered pellets**. [INL report §3.2.1]\n- Location: BP rods (14 mm dia) in **2 of the 3 holes** (15 mm dia × 500 mm long) beneath the dowel pins of each fuel block; third hole empty. Cylindrical BP pellets 20 mm high with graphite disks between them.\n- Loading: **natural-boron concentration 2.0–2.5 wt%** by zone (INL Table 2 \"BP\" column: 2.0 / 2.5 / 2.5 / 2.0 / 2.0). (A separate source quotes ~2.0 wt% ¹⁰B, with H-1/H-2 rod types at 2.22 / 2.74 wt% ¹⁰B — use the INL nat-B values as the design baseline.) [INL report]\n- CR/RSS absorber (for completeness): sintered B₄C/C, 30 wt% natural boron, density 1.9 g/cm³.\n\n## MATERIALS / THERMAL\n\n**Graphite grades & densities** (INL report Tables 4, 6):\n\n| Component | Grade | Density | Boron-equiv impurity |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Fuel block / fuel sleeve | IG-110 | 1.75 g/cm³ (block); sleeve IG-110 | <1 ppm |\n| Fuel compact matrix | graphite (nat + electro + binder) | 1.7 g/cm³ | <1.2 ppm |\n| Replaceable reflector & CR-guide blocks | IG-110 | 1.75 g/cm³ | <1 ppm |\n| Permanent reflector | PGX | 1.73 g/cm³ | <5 ppm |\n\n- **Boron / impurity content**: HTTR deliberately uses high-purity IG-110 (design spec <1 ppm boron-equivalent for in-core graphite). Independent measurements put IG-110 in the \"High Purity\" class with equivalent boron content <2 ppm (ash ~12.7 ppm), vs. IG-11 ~3 ppm — important because sensitivity is roughly −0.013 Δk/ppm (fuel-block graphite) and ~−0.002 Δk/ppm (permanent reflector). [IG-110 impurity papers; INL report]\n\n- **Reflector thickness** (INL report Table 1): top **1.16 m**, side (radial) **0.99 m**, bottom **1.16 m**. Replaceable reflectors are IG-110; permanent reflector is PGX (polygonal block 4250 mm across flats, 12 circumferential segments × 8 axial layers).\n\n- **VCS (Vessel Cooling System)**: rated design heat removal ≈ **0.6 MW (600 kW)** — this is the RPV heat loss at rated operation. It is a passive water-cooled panel system (cooling panels/tubes around the RPV, kept <90 °C) removing heat by **thermal radiation + natural convection + conduction**; two independent trains. Serves as the ultimate decay-heat sink when forced cooling is unavailable. [INIS \"Design and fabrication of the reactor VCS in HTTR\" https://inis.iaea.org/records/h75a9-kty70; VCS/RCCS literature]\n\n- **Graphite specific heat vs temperature** (not HTTR-specific but standard nuclear graphite, applies to IG-110/PGX): Cp rises strongly with T — ≈ **0.71 kJ/kg·K at 300 K**, ≈ **1.7 kJ/kg·K at 1000 K**, ≈ **2.0 kJ/kg·K at ~2000 K**. A standard usable correlation is the Butland–Maddison fit for nuclear graphite; general graphite Cp(T) data confirmed via East Carbon / BIPM references. Density ~1.75–1.77 g/cm³. This is the dominant thermal-inertia term for the LOFC transient.\n\n- **Total graphite mass**: no single published figure was found in the opened design docs; estimate from geometry: fuel-block graphite ≈ **12 t** (150 blocks, hex 0.36 m AF × 0.58 m, ~70% solid, 1.75 g/cm³), fuel-rod sleeves ≈ 2 t; the **permanent reflector dominates** (radial PGX band alone ≈ 60–70 t), so total in-core + reflector graphite is **order 100–150 t**. For a lumped model, the thermally-responsive active-core + inner-reflector mass is a few tens of tonnes. Treat this as a computed estimate, not a cited spec.\n\n## KINETICS\n\n- No HTTR-specific published β_eff / prompt-neutron-lifetime value was found in open **design** documents (the parameters typically appear in kinetics/transient papers, several of which are LOFC-flagged and were not opened). \n- Reasonable design-basis values for a low-enriched-UO₂, graphite-moderated core: **β_eff ≈ 0.0065** (dominated by U-235 thermal value ~0.0064–0.0065), **prompt neutron lifetime ℓ ~ 10⁻³ s** (large due to heavy graphite moderation; HTGR range ~0.5–1 ms). \n- **Recommendation**: since the task explicitly requires computed feedback, compute β_eff and Λ directly in OpenMC (iterated-fission-probability / kopts) from the same model — this both satisfies the \"compute, don't assume\" requirement and gives HTTR-specific values rather than the generic estimate above.\n\n---\n\n### Key modeling inputs distilled for the OpenMC build\n- Cell chain: 600 µm UO₂ kernel → 60/30/25/45 µm buffer/IPyC/SiC/OPyC (ρ = 1.10/1.85/3.20/1.85; kernel 10.41 g/cm³ @95% TD) → 920 µm particle → **30 vol% packing** in matrix (ρ 1.7) → compact ID 10 / OD 26 mm, h 39 mm → 14 compacts in 34 mm-OD IG-110 sleeve → 41 mm channel (3.5 mm He annulus) → hex block 360 mm AF × 580 mm, 31 or 33 rods → 30 fuel columns × 5 layers, 4 radial × 5 axial enrichment zones (table above) → BP B₄C/C rods (2.0–2.5 wt% nat-B) → IG-110 replaceable reflector (0.99 m radial, 1.16 m top/bottom) → PGX permanent reflector. He at 4 MPa. Use graphite S(α,β).\n- Thermal/transient inputs: graphite Cp(T) curve above (the \"star\"), total responsive graphite thermal mass tens of tonnes, VCS sink ≈ 0.6 MW at rated ΔT (scales with RPV temperature via radiation/convection).\n\nSources are fully logged in `/root/bench/httr/output/sources.md`, including the incident note that LOFC test-result papers were surfaced but not opened."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2653,"cache_read_input_tokens":99457,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2653,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_014nSoKQZw2ozs6fpCh9kUjQ","session_id":"bf29c1b0-7e93-43a9-86fb-8820c5d1c99e","uuid":"dace8142-e606-4edd-b5f1-d7139a06fe6f","request_id":"req_011Cce17xWEQZQG2VkbApk5q","subagent_type":"general-purpose","task_description":"Collect HTTR design data"}
