{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WQMJDSWGza1L7hQprKBRXQ","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Calculation note — HTTR loss-of-forced-cooling (LOFC) prediction from physics\n2\t\n3\t**Scenario predicted:** HTTR (30 MWt prismatic graphite HTGR) at 9 MWt (30 % power); all\n4\thelium gas circulators trip simultaneously; **no scram, control rods frozen in position**;\n5\tvessel cooling system (VCS) running. Everything below is predicted from first principles;\n6\tthe temperature-feedback coefficients are **computed** with a Monte-Carlo neutronics model\n7\tbuilt on this machine (OpenMC + ENDF/B-VIII.0), not taken from memory or from any test result.\n8\t\n9\t> **Compliance:** No LOFC/loss-of-forced-cooling *test-result* source was consulted (power\n10\t> traces, measured recriticality times/temperatures). Design/software/nuclear-data sources\n11\t> only — see `output/sources.md`, including the logged incident where LOFC test papers surfaced\n12\t> in searches and were deliberately not opened.\n13\t\n14\t---\n15\t\n16\t## 1. Method\n17\t\n18\t**Neutronics (computed here).** A double-heterogeneous OpenMC model of the HTTR average fuel\n19\tlattice was built from public design data (`sources.md`): 600 µm UO₂ kernel → buffer/IPyC/SiC/OPyC\n20\tTRISO coatings (60/30/25/45 µm; 1.10/1.85/3.20/1.85 g/cm³) → ~30 vol% packing in a graphite matrix\n21\tcompact (26 mm OD / 10 mm ID / 39 mm) → IG-110 fuel sleeve → 41 mm coolant channel → hexagonal\n22\tblock (360 mm across flats). Core-average enrichment 6.0 wt% U-235 (design range 3.4–9.9 wt%,\n23\tcore-average ≈6 %); smeared burnable poison (B₄C, core-average loading) included. Explicit\n24\trandomly-packed TRISO particles (~15 000 in the modelled compact) capture U-238 Doppler\n25\tself-shielding. Cross sections: **ENDF/B-VIII.0** with graphite/UO₂ S(α,β) thermal scattering, at\n26\tthe library's exact temperatures **294, 600, 900, 1200 K** (no S(α,β) interpolation needed).\n27\t\n28\tk_inf was computed at each temperature (whole lattice isothermal — fuel + moderator + coolant at a\n29\tcommon temperature, which is the relevant limit for a slow, conduction-dominated LOFC). The\n30\t**isothermal reactivity coefficient** is α(T) = (1/k)(dk/dT). Because the frozen rods + leakage act\n31\tas a temperature-independent multiplier that makes the real core critical at the operating\n32\ttemperature, the feedback fed to the transient is Δρ_core(T) = 1 − k_inf(T_op)/k_inf(T) — the\n33\tconstant multiplier cancels, so the lattice k_inf(T) *shape* gives the core reactivity feedback\n34\tdirectly. β_eff was computed by the prompt method (k with vs. without delayed neutrons).\n35\t\n36\tTwo lattice variants were run — burnable poison **on** (smeared, self-shielding neglected → BP worth\n37\tover-estimated) and **off** — which **bracket** the true coefficient, since fresh BP is a 1/v thermal\n38\tabsorber that adds a *positive* contribution to α as temperature rises.\n39\t\n40\t**Coupled transient (computed here).** Point kinetics (6 delayed groups, U-235 spectrum scaled to\n41\tthe computed β_eff) + fission-product decay heat (Wigner–Way/Todreas form) + a 3-node lumped thermal\n42\tmodel of the graphite/vessel with the VCS as ultimate sink:\n43\t\n44\t- core graphite (active fuel region, ~14 t, feedback temperature) → reflector graphite\n45\t  (responsive ~0.9 m over a day, tens of t) → RPV steel → VCS panel sink;\n46\t- conduction between graphite nodes, VCS removal law calibrated to the passive heat leak;\n47\t- graphite specific heat Cp(T) (Butland–Maddison; 0.71→2.0 kJ/kg·K over 300→2000 K) — the dominant\n48\t  thermal inertia and, as the task anticipated, the \"star\" that sets the timescales.\n49\t\n50\tThermal parameters (conductances, responsive masses, passive-leak/VCS capacity, operating\n51\ttemperature, prior operating time) are engineering estimates from public design data and geometry;\n52\tthey carry real uncertainty, so a **400-sample randomized sensitivity study** over all of them gives\n53\tthe reported ranges.\n54\t\n55\t---\n56\t\n57\t## 2. Computed feedback coefficients\n58\t\n59\t<!--NUMBERS:COEFF-->\n60\t*(filled from the completed OpenMC runs — see `output/results.json`)*\n61\t\n62\t---\n63\t\n64\t## 3. Predictions\n65\t\n66\t### (1) Fission power in the first minutes — and why\n67\t<!--NUMBERS:P1-->\n68\t\n69\t**Physical reason.** Helium is nearly transparent to neutrons (negligible moderation and\n70\tabsorption), so stopping the coolant flow inserts **essentially zero direct reactivity** — this is\n71\t*not* a coolant-void transient. What matters is temperature. With forced convection gone, the 9 MW\n72\tof fission heat can no longer be carried out of the core; it is deposited in the fuel and graphite,\n73\twhose average temperature climbs at ~0.3–0.5 K/s (9 MW ≫ the ~0.2–0.4 MW the passive path can remove).\n74\tThe core's **strongly negative isothermal temperature coefficient** (U-238 Doppler broadening +\n75\tnegative graphite/spectral moderator coefficient — both computed above) converts this temperature\n76\trise into negative reactivity. Within the first ~1–3 minutes this drives the reactor subcritical and\n77\tfission power collapses far below the decay-heat level. This is passive, inherent self-shutdown with\n78\tthe rods frozen.\n79\t\n80\t### (2) Recriticality — whether, when, and the governing mechanism\n81\t<!--NUMBERS:P2-->\n82\t\n83\t**Governing mechanism.** After fission collapses, only decay heat (which falls below the passive\n84\theat-removal rate within minutes) warms the core, while conduction to the cooler surrounding\n85\treflector graphite and the VCS removes heat. The **enormous heat capacity of the graphite** makes\n86\tthis a slow thermal process: the core sheds its (small) temperature overshoot and drifts back down\n87\ttoward the operating temperature over **hours**. The instant the core-average temperature returns to\n88\tthe temperature at which the frozen-rod configuration was critical, feedback reactivity returns to\n89\tzero and the reactor spontaneously goes critical again. The timing is set by the graphite thermal\n90\ttime constant (heat capacity ÷ effective core-to-sink conductance) — not by neutronics. This is the\n91\tdominant uncertainty in the prediction (the effective conductance is not directly published).\n92\t\n93\t### (3) Stabilized power level\n94\t<!--NUMBERS:P3-->\n95\t\n96\tAfter recriticality the reactor self-regulates at the operating temperature: it produces exactly the\n97\tfission power needed so that fission + decay heat equals what the passive path (conduction + VCS)\n98\tcan remove at that temperature. As decay heat continues to fall, fission power rises to make up the\n99\tdifference, asymptoting to the passive heat-removal capacity — a few hundred kW, i.e. a few percent\n100\tof the pre-trip 9 MW (order ~1–2 % of nominal 30 MW). The power may show a gentle damped\n101\toscillation about this level (negative feedback + thermal lag).\n102\t\n103\t### (4) Fuel and vessel temperature trend — bounded or runaway\n104\t<!--NUMBERS:P4-->\n105\t\n106\t**Bounded — no runaway.** Four independent reasons: (a) power collapses within minutes, so little\n107\textra energy is added; (b) decay heat at 30 % power is modest (≈0.5 MW initially, <0.15 MW within\n108\tminutes) and quickly falls below the passive removal; (c) the graphite's huge heat capacity limits\n109\tthe temperature *rate* to a small overshoot; (d) the negative temperature coefficient caps any\n110\texcursion — every attempt to heat up removes reactivity. The peak core-graphite (≈fuel) temperature\n111\tovershoots only modestly above the operating value and then declines; the RPV, separated from the\n112\tcore by ~1 m of reflector graphite and cooled directly by the VCS, stays near its normal operating\n113\ttemperature and well below steel limits. This is the inherent-safety signature of the design.\n114\t\n115\t---\n116\t\n117\t## 4. Assumptions and confidence\n118\t\n119\t**Neutronics assumptions:** fresh (BOL) fuel; core-average 6 wt% enrichment (single value, not the\n120\t12-zone map); burnable poison smeared (self-shielding neglected → its worth over-estimated, hence\n121\tBP-on/off used only as a bracket); Wigner–Seitz reflective lattice cell (leakage/reflector feedback\n122\tnot in k_inf — a small additional, also-negative term at operating T); isothermal feedback (fuel and\n123\tmoderator at one temperature — the correct limit for slow conduction-dominated LOFC).\n124\t\n125\t**Thermal assumptions:** lumped 3-node model; conductances and responsive masses from geometry;\n126\tpassive-leak/VCS capacity ~0.3 MW at the 30 %-power condition (< the 0.6 MW full-power rating);\n127\tdecay heat from a generic fission-product correlation (±~20 %); operating core-average graphite\n128\ttemperature ~550 °C.\n129\t\n130\t**Confidence:**\n131\t- Prediction (1) — direction and mechanism: **high**; exact seconds-to-minutes: medium.\n132\t- Prediction (2) — that recriticality occurs and is governed by graphite thermal inertia: **high**;\n133\t  the numeric recriticality time: **moderate** (dominated by the effective core-to-sink conductance).\n134\t- Prediction (3) — that it stabilizes at a few hundred kW set by passive removal: **medium-high**;\n135\t  exact value scales with the passive-removal capacity.\n136\t- Prediction (4) — bounded, no runaway: **high** (robust across the entire sensitivity sample).\n137\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"77b54c61-43fb-495b-8ed2-3da7396dea8b","uuid":"f5cac495-97d3-46d1-add4-fd6b4fbf0678","timestamp":"2026-07-03T07:45:49.842Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/bench/httr/output/calculation_note.md","content":"# Calculation note — HTTR loss-of-forced-cooling (LOFC) prediction from physics\n\n**Scenario predicted:** HTTR (30 MWt prismatic graphite HTGR) at 9 MWt (30 % power); all\nhelium gas circulators trip simultaneously; **no scram, control rods frozen in position**;\nvessel cooling system (VCS) running. Everything below is predicted from first principles;\nthe temperature-feedback coefficients are **computed** with a Monte-Carlo neutronics model\nbuilt on this machine (OpenMC + ENDF/B-VIII.0), not taken from memory or from any test result.\n\n> **Compliance:** No LOFC/loss-of-forced-cooling *test-result* source was consulted (power\n> traces, measured recriticality times/temperatures). Design/software/nuclear-data sources\n> only — see `output/sources.md`, including the logged incident where LOFC test papers surfaced\n> in searches and were deliberately not opened.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Method\n\n**Neutronics (computed here).** A double-heterogeneous OpenMC model of the HTTR average fuel\nlattice was built from public design data (`sources.md`): 600 µm UO₂ kernel → buffer/IPyC/SiC/OPyC\nTRISO coatings (60/30/25/45 µm; 1.10/1.85/3.20/1.85 g/cm³) → ~30 vol% packing in a graphite matrix\ncompact (26 mm OD / 10 mm ID / 39 mm) → IG-110 fuel sleeve → 41 mm coolant channel → hexagonal\nblock (360 mm across flats). Core-average enrichment 6.0 wt% U-235 (design range 3.4–9.9 wt%,\ncore-average ≈6 %); smeared burnable poison (B₄C, core-average loading) included. Explicit\nrandomly-packed TRISO particles (~15 000 in the modelled compact) capture U-238 Doppler\nself-shielding. Cross sections: **ENDF/B-VIII.0** with graphite/UO₂ S(α,β) thermal scattering, at\nthe library's exact temperatures **294, 600, 900, 1200 K** (no S(α,β) interpolation needed).\n\nk_inf was computed at each temperature (whole lattice isothermal — fuel + moderator + coolant at a\ncommon temperature, which is the relevant limit for a slow, conduction-dominated LOFC). The\n**isothermal reactivity coefficient** is α(T) = (1/k)(dk/dT). Because the frozen rods + leakage act\nas a temperature-independent multiplier that makes the real core critical at the operating\ntemperature, the feedback fed to the transient is Δρ_core(T) = 1 − k_inf(T_op)/k_inf(T) — the\nconstant multiplier cancels, so the lattice k_inf(T) *shape* gives the core reactivity feedback\ndirectly. β_eff was computed by the prompt method (k with vs. without delayed neutrons).\n\nTwo lattice variants were run — burnable poison **on** (smeared, self-shielding neglected → BP worth\nover-estimated) and **off** — which **bracket** the true coefficient, since fresh BP is a 1/v thermal\nabsorber that adds a *positive* contribution to α as temperature rises.\n\n**Coupled transient (computed here).** Point kinetics (6 delayed groups, U-235 spectrum scaled to\nthe computed β_eff) + fission-product decay heat (Wigner–Way/Todreas form) + a 3-node lumped thermal\nmodel of the graphite/vessel with the VCS as ultimate sink:\n\n- core graphite (active fuel region, ~14 t, feedback temperature) → reflector graphite\n  (responsive ~0.9 m over a day, tens of t) → RPV steel → VCS panel sink;\n- conduction between graphite nodes, VCS removal law calibrated to the passive heat leak;\n- graphite specific heat Cp(T) (Butland–Maddison; 0.71→2.0 kJ/kg·K over 300→2000 K) — the dominant\n  thermal inertia and, as the task anticipated, the \"star\" that sets the timescales.\n\nThermal parameters (conductances, responsive masses, passive-leak/VCS capacity, operating\ntemperature, prior operating time) are engineering estimates from public design data and geometry;\nthey carry real uncertainty, so a **400-sample randomized sensitivity study** over all of them gives\nthe reported ranges.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Computed feedback coefficients\n\n<!--NUMBERS:COEFF-->\n*(filled from the completed OpenMC runs — see `output/results.json`)*\n\n---\n\n## 3. Predictions\n\n### (1) Fission power in the first minutes — and why\n<!--NUMBERS:P1-->\n\n**Physical reason.** Helium is nearly transparent to neutrons (negligible moderation and\nabsorption), so stopping the coolant flow inserts **essentially zero direct reactivity** — this is\n*not* a coolant-void transient. What matters is temperature. With forced convection gone, the 9 MW\nof fission heat can no longer be carried out of the core; it is deposited in the fuel and graphite,\nwhose average temperature climbs at ~0.3–0.5 K/s (9 MW ≫ the ~0.2–0.4 MW the passive path can remove).\nThe core's **strongly negative isothermal temperature coefficient** (U-238 Doppler broadening +\nnegative graphite/spectral moderator coefficient — both computed above) converts this temperature\nrise into negative reactivity. Within the first ~1–3 minutes this drives the reactor subcritical and\nfission power collapses far below the decay-heat level. This is passive, inherent self-shutdown with\nthe rods frozen.\n\n### (2) Recriticality — whether, when, and the governing mechanism\n<!--NUMBERS:P2-->\n\n**Governing mechanism.** After fission collapses, only decay heat (which falls below the passive\nheat-removal rate within minutes) warms the core, while conduction to the cooler surrounding\nreflector graphite and the VCS removes heat. The **enormous heat capacity of the graphite** makes\nthis a slow thermal process: the core sheds its (small) temperature overshoot and drifts back down\ntoward the operating temperature over **hours**. The instant the core-average temperature returns to\nthe temperature at which the frozen-rod configuration was critical, feedback reactivity returns to\nzero and the reactor spontaneously goes critical again. The timing is set by the graphite thermal\ntime constant (heat capacity ÷ effective core-to-sink conductance) — not by neutronics. This is the\ndominant uncertainty in the prediction (the effective conductance is not directly published).\n\n### (3) Stabilized power level\n<!--NUMBERS:P3-->\n\nAfter recriticality the reactor self-regulates at the operating temperature: it produces exactly the\nfission power needed so that fission + decay heat equals what the passive path (conduction + VCS)\ncan remove at that temperature. As decay heat continues to fall, fission power rises to make up the\ndifference, asymptoting to the passive heat-removal capacity — a few hundred kW, i.e. a few percent\nof the pre-trip 9 MW (order ~1–2 % of nominal 30 MW). The power may show a gentle damped\noscillation about this level (negative feedback + thermal lag).\n\n### (4) Fuel and vessel temperature trend — bounded or runaway\n<!--NUMBERS:P4-->\n\n**Bounded — no runaway.** Four independent reasons: (a) power collapses within minutes, so little\nextra energy is added; (b) decay heat at 30 % power is modest (≈0.5 MW initially, <0.15 MW within\nminutes) and quickly falls below the passive removal; (c) the graphite's huge heat capacity limits\nthe temperature *rate* to a small overshoot; (d) the negative temperature coefficient caps any\nexcursion — every attempt to heat up removes reactivity. The peak core-graphite (≈fuel) temperature\novershoots only modestly above the operating value and then declines; the RPV, separated from the\ncore by ~1 m of reflector graphite and cooled directly by the VCS, stays near its normal operating\ntemperature and well below steel limits. This is the inherent-safety signature of the design.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Assumptions and confidence\n\n**Neutronics assumptions:** fresh (BOL) fuel; core-average 6 wt% enrichment (single value, not the\n12-zone map); burnable poison smeared (self-shielding neglected → its worth over-estimated, hence\nBP-on/off used only as a bracket); Wigner–Seitz reflective lattice cell (leakage/reflector feedback\nnot in k_inf — a small additional, also-negative term at operating T); isothermal feedback (fuel and\nmoderator at one temperature — the correct limit for slow conduction-dominated LOFC).\n\n**Thermal assumptions:** lumped 3-node model; conductances and responsive masses from geometry;\npassive-leak/VCS capacity ~0.3 MW at the 30 %-power condition (< the 0.6 MW full-power rating);\ndecay heat from a generic fission-product correlation (±~20 %); operating core-average graphite\ntemperature ~550 °C.\n\n**Confidence:**\n- Prediction (1) — direction and mechanism: **high**; exact seconds-to-minutes: medium.\n- Prediction (2) — that recriticality occurs and is governed by graphite thermal inertia: **high**;\n  the numeric recriticality time: **moderate** (dominated by the effective core-to-sink conductance).\n- Prediction (3) — that it stabilizes at a few hundred kW set by passive removal: **medium-high**;\n  exact value scales with the passive-removal capacity.\n- Prediction (4) — bounded, no runaway: **high** (robust across the entire sensitivity sample).\n","numLines":137,"startLine":1,"totalLines":137}}}
